eir lens on Israeli state violence, propelled by a shared dream: that advances in digital photography—closer, sharper, faster—would advance their respective political agendas. Most would be let down. Drawing on ethnographic work, Rebecca L. Stein chronicles Palestinian video-activists seeking justice, Israeli soldiers laboring to perfect the military's image, and Zionist conspiracy theorists accusing Palestinians of "playing dead." Writing against techno-optimism, Stein investigates what camera dreams and disillusionment across these political divides reveal about the Israeli and Palestinian colonial present, and the shifting terms of power and struggle in the smartphone age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-xMass media and the conflict. 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-xPhotography. 0aDocumentary photographyxPolitical aspectszIsrael. 0aDocumentary photographyxPolitical aspectszPalestine. 0aPolitical violencezIsrael. 0aPolitical violencezPalestine. 0aVideo recordingsxPolitical aspectszIsrael. 0aVideo recordingsxPolitical aspectszPalestine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh  aDigital media.  aGaza.  aIsraeli military.  aPalestine.  acitizen journalism.  ahuman rights.  asettler colonialism.  asocial movements.  asurveillance.  avisual politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University P